_No response_

## Description

Compiling the ~100-line file below at `-O` with Apple Swift 6.3.3 (swiftlang-6.3.3.1.3, Xcode 26.6) crashes `swift-frontend` (SIGABRT): the SIL ownership verifier run by **CopyPropagation** fails with `Found outside of lifetime use?!`. `-Onone` compiles fine.

The verifier complaint is that a `load_borrow`ed `String` is passed as a **@guaranteed phi argument** by a `br` that executes **after** the value's `end_borrow`:

```
Found outside of lifetime use?!
Value:   %171 = load_borrow %170 : $*String              // users: %174, %173
Consuming User:   end_borrow %171 : $String                       // id: %173
Non Consuming User:   br bb15(%169 : $Optional<ActivityJSONValue>, %171 : $String) // id: %174
Block: bb12
```

The invalid SIL is already present in CopyPropagation's *input* (see SIL analysis below), so an earlier pass appears to produce it and CopyPropagation's post-run verification is merely the first to notice — same dynamic as noted in #90408.

This was originally hit building a real app (first Release/archive build of the project): identical crash for both an iOS-simulator destination and a native macOS destination of the same code. The single-file reproducer below is distilled from that app and was verified against the iOS simulator target.

**Workaround:** rewriting the `.map { } ?? .null` helper as an `if let` expression avoids the crash (behavior identical):

```swift
nonisolated func jsonValue(_ string: String?) -> ActivityJSONValue {
    if let string { .string(string) } else { .null }
}
```

## Reproduction

`repro.swift` (self-contained; needs the iOS simulator SDK for the SwiftUI import):

```swift
import SwiftUI


nonisolated enum ActivityJSONValue: Hashable, Sendable {
    case string(String)
    case null
}

nonisolated struct ActivityChange: Hashable, Sendable {
    let old: ActivityJSONValue?
    let new: ActivityJSONValue?
}

nonisolated struct HouseholdMember: Identifiable, Hashable, Sendable {
    let id: UUID
    var color: String
}
enum DemoError: Error {
    case notFound
}

struct DemoDataService: DataServiceProtocol {
    let store: DemoDataStore

    func updateMyProfile(memberId: UUID, color: String?) async throws -> HouseholdMember {
        try applyProfileUpdate(memberId: memberId, color: color)
    }

    func applyProfileUpdate(memberId: UUID, color: String?) throws -> HouseholdMember {
        let index = 0
        let old = store.members[index]
        if let color { store.members[index].color = color }

        let updated = store.members[index]
        var changes: [String: ActivityChange] = [:]
        changes["color"] = ActivityChange(
            old: jsonValue(old.color), new: jsonValue(updated.color))
        _ = changes
        return updated
    }
}
@MainActor
final class DemoDataStore {
    var members: [HouseholdMember] = []
}

nonisolated func jsonValue(_ string: String?) -> ActivityJSONValue {
    string.map { .string($0) } ?? .null
}

enum AppServices {
    nonisolated(unsafe) static var dataService: any DataServiceProtocol = MainActor.assumeIsolated { DemoDataService(store: DemoDataStore()) }
}

protocol DataServiceProtocol: Sendable {
    func updateMyProfile(memberId: UUID, color: String?) async throws -> HouseholdMember
}

final class HouseholdViewModel {
    var currentMember: HouseholdMember?
}

final class MemberViewModel {
    var householdViewModel: HouseholdViewModel?

    let dataService: any DataServiceProtocol

    init(dataService: any DataServiceProtocol = AppServices.dataService) {
        self.dataService = dataService
    }

    @MainActor
    func updateMyProfile(color: String?) async -> Bool {
        guard let household = householdViewModel,
              let member = household.currentMember else { return false }

        do {
            _ = try await dataService.updateMyProfile(
                memberId: member.id,
                color: color
            )
            return true
        } catch {
            return false
        }
    }
}

struct EditProfileView: View {
    let member: MemberViewModel

    var body: some View {
        Button("Save") {
            Task {
                _ = await member.updateMyProfile(color: "#FF0000")
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Command (flag set from the originating app's Release configuration; crashes in ~2 s):

```bash
xcrun swiftc -O -wmo -g -swift-version 6 -default-isolation MainActor \
  -enable-upcoming-feature NonisolatedNonsendingByDefault \
  -enable-upcoming-feature InferIsolatedConformances \
  -enable-upcoming-feature MemberImportVisibility \
  -enable-experimental-feature DebugDescriptionMacro \
  -profile-generate -profile-coverage-mapping \
  -Xfrontend -enable-default-cmo \
  -target arm64-apple-ios26.1-simulator \
  -sdk "$(xcrun --sdk iphonesimulator --show-sdk-path)" \
  -module-name Bank_of_Quack -c repro.swift -o repro.o
```

The set above is the app's actual Release configuration, reproduced deterministically. `-Onone` (or `@_optimize(none)` on `applyProfileUpdate`) does not crash. See *Flag minimization* below — only `-O` plus `-default-isolation MainActor` are actually needed.

### Load-bearing ingredients

Each of these was verified independently — removing any one makes the crash disappear:

- the SwiftUI `View` whose `Button` action closure spawns the `Task` that awaits the chain (the identical chain called from a plain function does **not** crash);
- the async-throws hop through the `any DataServiceProtocol` existential (View → `@MainActor` class → existential → struct witness → method);
- **both** `jsonValue(String?)` calls in the `ActivityChange(old:new:)` initializer, with **non-optional** `String`s implicitly promoted to `String?` at the call sites;
- the `Dictionary` insertion (`_ = ActivityChange(...)` alone is clean);
- `ActivityChange`'s fields being `Optional` (`ActivityJSONValue?`) — non-optional fields compile fine;
- reading the `String`-field struct out of the `@MainActor` class's array.

### Flag minimization

A remove-one-group/greedy matrix over the Release flag set shows none of the extra flags matter: `-g`, `-profile-generate -profile-coverage-mapping`, `-Xfrontend -enable-default-cmo`, the three upcoming features (`NonisolatedNonsendingByDefault`, `InferIsolatedConformances`, `MemberImportVisibility`), `-enable-experimental-feature DebugDescriptionMacro`, `-swift-version 6`, and even `-wmo` are each droppable individually **and all at once** — the crash persists. Minimal crashing command:

```bash
xcrun swiftc -O -default-isolation MainActor \
  -target arm64-apple-ios26.1-simulator \
  -sdk "$(xcrun --sdk iphonesimulator --show-sdk-path)" \
  -module-name Bank_of_Quack -c repro.swift -o repro.o
```

`-default-isolation MainActor` can't be dropped only because the file no longer type-checks without it, so it is required to build rather than shown to be load-bearing for the optimizer bug. The same minimal set also crashes compiling for native macOS against the macOS SDK (no `-target`, `-sdk "$(xcrun --sdk macosx --show-sdk-path)"`).

## Expected behavior

Successful compile — the source is valid Swift; it compiles at `-Onone`, and compiles at `-O` with the `if let` form of `jsonValue`.

