### Description

I have following code in Swift:

```swift
@objc
public class SomeObject: NSObject {
    public override init() {
        super.init()
    }

    public func someMethod() {
        print("object invoked")
    }
}

@objc
public class ObjCWrapper: NSObject {
    @objc
    public func sendingMethod(_ val: sending Any) {
        // do nothing
    }
}
```

I am creating SomeObject and passing it to ObjCWrapper.sendingMethod in Objective C:

```objectivec
@implementation ObjCCode

- (void)startScenario {
    SomeObject *obj = [[SomeObject alloc] init];

    ObjCWrapper *wrapper = [[ObjCWrapper alloc] init];
    NSLog(@"SomeObject address: %p", obj);
    [wrapper sendingMethod:obj];

    [NSTimer scheduledTimerWithTimeInterval:5.0
                                    repeats:YES
                                      block:^(NSTimer * _Nonnull timer) {
        NSLog(@"SomeObject address: %p", obj);
    }];
}

@end
```

When I invoke ObjCCode().startScenario() from Swift I get:

> Task 1: EXC_BAD_ACCESS (code=1, address=0x528c7a8e0)

It seems like in case sending in Swift, ARC counter is not updated when object is passed from Objective C. Similar logic in Swift doesn't cause any crash, e.g. Implementing startScenario in Swift doesn't cause any crash:

```swift
